Introduction¶

Dataset:¶

This movie database contains information about 10,000 movies including genres, ratings, revenue, budget, and more. It contains movies which are released between 1960 and 2015, it also has two columns for budget and revenue in terms of 2010 dollars accounting for inflation over time which will be used in my analysis.

Questions:¶

  • how are the budget of making a movie changed over time?
  • Which movies have the most and least profit?
  • Which genres are most popular from year to year?
  • What are Average runtime, budget and revenue of all the movies?
  • What are the average runtimes of movies over the years?
  • Which Runtime movies is most liked by the audiences according to the popularity?
  • Which Production Companies have the highst profit?
  • Which director has the most popular movies?
  • Most Popular Keywords?
  • What kinds of properties are associated with movies that have high revenues?

First thoughts¶

  • Some columns aren't needed in the analysis which i will drop (id, imdb_id, budget, revenue, cast, homepage, tagline, overview, release_date, vote_count, vote_average)
  • number of votes differ for each movie , so vote_count and vote_average might not be useful.
  • some rows have NaN values which i will drop.
  • some rows has 0 budget and revanue which i think is a missing data so i will drop them too.
  • there is only 1 duplicate row which i will drop.

Question 1: How are the budget of making a movie changed over time?¶

In [11]:
#plotting barplot for Average Budget over time
x=df.groupby('release_year').budget_adj.mean().index
h=df.groupby('release_year').budget_adj.mean().values
plt.figure(figsize=(16,8))
plt.bar(x=x,height=h);
plt.xlabel('Release Year',size=15)
plt.xticks(size=12)
plt.ylabel('Budget (Adj)',size=15)
plt.yticks(size=12)
plt.title('Average Spending over Time',size=16);
The above figure shows ups and downs then a growth in spending starting around 1970s.¶
In [12]:
#Plot data and a linear regression model fit for spending over time
df_bud = df.query("release_year > 1970").groupby('release_year').budget_adj.mean()
x=df_bud.index
y=df_bud.values
plt.figure(figsize=(16,8))
sns.regplot(x,y)
plt.xlabel('Release Year',size=15)
plt.xticks(size=12)
plt.ylabel('Budget (Adj)',size=15)
plt.yticks(size=12)
plt.title('Average Spending over Time',size=16);

From the figures above, spending is growing over time and has a peak average in 1997 ~ 1999.¶

Question 10: What kinds of properties are associated with movies that have high revenues?¶

In [28]:
#plotting scatterplot to find properties that associated with high revenues movies
fig, axes = plt.subplots(2,2,figsize = (16,8))
x=df['revenue_adj']
fig.suptitle("Revenue Vs (Budget,Runtime,Popularity)",fontsize=14)
sns.regplot(x, y=df['budget_adj'],ax=axes[0,0])
sns.regplot(x, y=df['runtime'],ax=axes[1,0])
sns.regplot(x, y=df['popularity'],ax=axes[0,1])
sns.set_style("whitegrid")
In [29]:
#correlation heatmap to find properties that associated with high revenues movies 
corr = df[['revenue_adj','budget_adj','popularity','runtime']].corr()
plt.figure(figsize=(16, 6))
heatmap = sns.heatmap(corr,annot=True)
heatmap.set_title('Revenue Vs (Budget,Runtime,Popularity)', fontdict={'fontsize':15}, pad=12);

  • Budget vs Revenue:

    we can see that the revenues increase slightly at higher levels (moderate Correlation), So There is a possibility that movies with higher investments result in better revenues.

    Correlation = 0.57

  • Popularity vs Revenue:

    we can see that the revenue seems to be slightly increasing with popularity (moderate Correlation), We can say that movies with higher Popularity get higher revenue.

    Correlation = 0.54

  • Runtime vs Revenue:

    The correlation between revenue and runtime is 0.28 (weak corelation). So runtime is not highly related to the revenue.

Conclusions¶

We can summarize our findings in those few points:¶

  • Budget of making movies is increasing over time.
  • Star Wars is the most profitable movie ever.
  • Drama has the highest number of released movies followed by Comedy.
  • Most popular genres in each decade are:
    1. Drama
    2. Action
    3. Comedy
    4. Thriller
    5. Adventure
  • Runtime of a movie is decreasing over years , with average runtime arround 110 Minutes.
  • Movies in the range of 150-200 runtime are more popular than other movies.
  • Most Earning Film Production Companies are:
    1. Warner Bros
    2. Universal Picture
    3. Paramount Pictures
    4. 20th Century Studios
  • Directors with the most popular movies:
    1. Christopher Nolan
    2. Steven Spielberg
    3. Peter Jackson
    4. Quentin Tarantino
  • Movies with higher Budgets and Popularity have shown an increase in the revenues.

Limitation:¶

  • there are many data that was removed such as rows contained 0 and null values.
  • It should be noted that these this analysis does not imply any causation.
